 comprehensive view of the creation of a social hierarchy wherein the state classified immigrants to the Chinese county of Shuangcheng into distinct categories, each associated with different land entitlements. The resulting patterns of wealth stratification and social hierarchy were then simultaneously challenged and reinforced by local people. The tensions built into the unequal land entitlements shaped the identities of immigrant groups, and this social hierarchy persisted even after the institution of unequal state entitlements was removed. State-Sponsored Inequality offers an in-depth understanding of the key factors that contribute to social stratification in agrarian societies. Moreover, it sheds light on the many parallels between the stratification system in nineteenth-century Shuangcheng and structural inequality in contemporary China.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aLand grantsxHistoryx19th centuryxChinaxManchuria. 0aLand grantszChinazManchuriaxHistoryy19th century. 0aLandownersxHistoryx19th centuryxChinaxManchuria. 0aLandownerszChinazManchuriaxHistoryy19th century. 0aSocial stratificationxHistoryx19th centuryxChinaxManchuria. 0aSocial stratificationzChinazManchuriaxHistoryy19th century. 0aWealthxHistoryx19th centuryxChinaxManchuria. 0aWealthzChinazManchuriaxHistoryy19th century. 4aEight Banners. 4aManchuria/Northeast China. 4aQing dynasty. 4aagrarian society. 4aentitlement. 4afrontier settlement. 4aland distribution. 4amigration. 4astructural inequality. 4awealth stratification. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Classes & Economic Disparity.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503601635zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruy